\subsection{Messages}
A set of $\Sexpr{length(unique(study1a_drink_df$QualtricsMsgID))}$ alcohol-related ($\Sexpr{study1a_drink_df %>% group_by(condition) %>% summarize(n_msgs=length(unique(QualtricsMsgID))) %>% summarize(first(n_msgs))}$/Valence: pro/anti-alcohol x Source: professional/peer-produced condition) and $\Sexpr{study1b_drink_df %>% filter(grepl('non',condition)) %>% summarize(length(unique(QualtricsURL)))}$ non-alcoholic messages (15/source condition) were generated. All stimuli consisted of a still image and a related hashtag. Images were purposefully sampled from public Instagram posts and prior research in order to manipulate valence (pro-/anti-/non-alcoholic) and source (professional/peer). Pro- and anti-alcohol images displayed alcohol or alcohol consumption in a positive or negative light, respectively. Non-alcoholic messages portrayed non-alcoholic beverages and/or their consumption in a positive light. Source was manipulated by sampling images from Instagram pages of businesses (e.g. alcohol brands) and international, English-language anti-(binge) drinking campaings studied in prior research (\cite{scholz_neural_2019}); professional sources) or from public Instagram accounts of 'normal' users (peer sources). Hashtags were manipulated to reinforce image condition (e.g. using brand names, campaign slogans, or hashtags commonly used on Instagram for content of the respective category) and to control the amount of text across conditions. 

To present these stimuli to participants, we placed them into visual templates. Specifically, in Studies 1a/b, and half of Study 2 trials for each participant, the template mimicked an Instagram post. For the second half of Study 2 trials, we placed images and hashtags in a template mimicking a Google search result where the hashtags were displayed as search terms. The purpose of this manipulation was to test the specificity of any results to the context of social media as opposed to general online environments. Note that, because we did not find any significant effects of this exploratory online platform factor, we are reporting results collapsing across media conditions.

To protect copyright interests of all original content creators, the stimulus set is not published here, but is available upon request. A table with descriptions of all stimuli and the stimulus source are available in our GitHub reproducibility package (https://anonymous.4open.science/r/PilotPaperTalkingDrinks-anonymize/).

