All studies employed within-subject designs. Per trial Study 1a ($N_{trials/person}$ = $\Sexpr{study1a_drink_df %>% group_by(pIDs) %>% count() %>% ungroup() %>% summarize(unique(n)[1])}$) and 1b ($N_{trials/person}$ = $\Sexpr{study1b_drink_df %>% group_by(pIDs) %>% count() %>% ungroup() %>% summarize(unique(n)[1])}$) participants first viewed a message (described above) and subsequently rated current alcohol craving, followed by one manipulation check item per experimental factor (manipulation checks described in Supplementary Materials), emotional responses, and familiarity. Messages shown to Study 1a participants were randomly chosen from the full set of alcohol-related messages and, across trials, implemented a 2 Valence (pro vs. anti-alcohol) x 2 Source (professional vs. peer-produced) full-factorial design. Messages shown to Study 1b participants were randomly chosen out of the full samples of alcoholic ($\Sexpr{study1b_drink_df %>% filter(!grepl('non',condition)) %>% group_by(pIDs) %>% count() %>% ungroup() %>% summarize(unique(n)[1])}$/person)) and non-alcoholic ($\Sexpr{study1b_drink_df %>% filter(grepl('non',condition)) %>% group_by(pIDs) %>% count() %>% ungroup() %>% summarize(unique(n)[1])}$/person) messages (described above) and implemented a 3 Valence (pro vs. anti vs. non-alcoholic) x 2 Source (professional vs. peer-produced) full-factorial design. 

Study 2 served as a pilot study for a neuroimaging experiment and thus employed a task optimized for that methodology. Per Study 2 trial ($N_{trials/person}$ = $\Sexpr{study2_logs %>% group_by(pID) %>% count() %>% ungroup() %>% summarize(unique(n)[1])}$), participants first viewed a message for 6 seconds, followed by a brief fixation period and, subsequently, a standardized alcohol ($\Sexpr{study2_logs %>% group_by(pID,type) %>% count() %>% filter(type=='alcohol') %>% ungroup() %>%summarize(first(n))}$ trials/person) or non-alcohol ($\Sexpr{study2_logs %>% group_by(pID,type) %>% count() %>% filter(type=='non-alcohol') %>% ungroup() %>%summarize(first(n))}$ trials/person) cue which was shown for 4 seconds. Standardized (non-)alcohol cues were sampled from the Amsterdam Beverage Picture Set (\cite{pronk_validation_2015}). After the first two seconds of cue exposure, participants were asked to rate their craving for the beverage displayed by the cue. Trials were separated by a fixation period. Supplementary Figure 1 provides a visualization of a Study 2 example trial. Messages shown to Study 2 participants were randomly chosen from a sub-set ($N_{messages}$ = $\Sexpr{study2_logs %>% group_by(pID) %>% count() %>% ungroup() %>% summarize(unique(n)[1])}$ per valence * source condition) of alcohol-related messages used in Study 1 and, across trials, implemented a 2 Valence (pro vs. anti-alcohol) x 2 Source (professional vs. peer-produced) x 2 Cue type (alcoholic vs. non-alcoholic) design.

\subsection{Self-Report Measures}
Craving was assessed across all three studies. In Studies 1a/b, craving was measured immediately after stimulus exposure: "Looking at this post makes me want to drink alcohol today." (Likert-type scale; 1= Not at all, 7 = Very much). In Study 2, craving was assessed after exposure to an alcoholic or non-alcoholic beverage cue using the prompt: "Imagine holding this drink. Rate: [Looking at this post] makes me want to drink this" (Likert-type scale; 1 = Not at all, 5 = Very much). 

Positive and negative emotions were assessed in Studies 1a/b with two items: "To what extent does this post make you feel the following?" [positive/negative] (Likert-type scale: 1 = Not at all, 7 = Very much).

Familiarity was assessed with two items in Studies 1a/1b: "To what extent do you agree or disagree with the following statements? This post..." [shows people that are like me/shows a situation I'm familiar with] (Likert-type scale: 1 = Totally disagree, 7 = Totally agree).

Drinking and binge drinking frequency in Study 1a/b were assessed using two items based on the NIAAA's "Task Force on Recommended Alcohol Questions" (adjusted for European drink sizes; \cite{niaaa_recommended_2003}). Study 2 participants completed the standardized Alcohol Use Disorder Identification Test (AUDIT; \cite{bohn_alcohol_1995}; For details, see GitHub reproducibility package https://anonymous.4open.science/r/PilotPaperTalkingDrinks-anonymize/).

\subsection{Data Analysis}

Analyses of the two manipulation checks measured in Study 1a/b confirmed that the stimuli were perceived as intended in terms of the manipulated factors valence and source (see Supplementary Materials). 

% Cronbach's alpha calculated in scripts/compute_alpha.R
To test effects of familiarity, we created a familiarity index by computing the average of the self-relevance and familiarity ratings per trial (Cronbach's alpha for item scores averaged on the stimulus-level = 0.97, 95\%CI[0.96,0.98]).

The within-subjects data were analysed using series of multi-level regression models as implemented in R's lmerTest package (\cite{kuznetsova_lmertest_2019}) to account for the nested structure of the data within participants, messages, and, where applicable, studies. Marginal means and post-hoc pairwise comparisons were computed using R's emmeans package (\cite{lenth_emmeans_2022}). Specific model equations are provided in the notes of tables reporting the relevant results or, if no table is provided, in the results section.

